tweet: @waitwherethe @DaykinRon1956 @karunchandhok @LewisHamilton A legitimate cause for what outcome though? That‚Äôs the key question here and the publicly available evidence surely raises serious concerns. That‚Äôs why it appears to be worthy of undergoing a proper judicial process.

name: Edd Straw
tweet: @tommillard @DaykinRon1956 @karunchandhok @LewisHamilton Exactly! But that‚Äôs perhaps all the more reason to challenge them so they can show publicly how tolerant the regimes are of protest. I understand entirely why it‚Äôs a difficult position for F1/FIA but it‚Äôs not for everyone else.

name: Edd Straw
tweet: @tommillard @DaykinRon1956 @karunchandhok @LewisHamilton As you're pointing out, it's a messy problem - in general there can be no hard line that is drawn. But I'd always err on the side of allowing protest provided it's within reason. What Hamilton did was not disruptive, after all.

name: Edd Straw
tweet: @tommillard @DaykinRon1956 @karunchandhok @LewisHamilton That is indeed F1's right. But I also think that one measure of a society/country is how they respond to such protests. If we're talking about countries putting on events, they are doing it for national prestige, among other reasons, so it's legitimate to challenge them

name: Edd Straw
tweet: @jakehardmansmom @LewisHamilton I would argue that it is making the case for that due process. And that appears to be a legitimate demand, looking at the comments made here for example   https://t.co/Im4CEN6EVS

name: Edd Straw

name: Edd Straw
tweet: @E_R_Podcast @SMitchellF1 @wearetherace @glennfreeman39 Marginal incidents are always contentious because then people's underlying position is key. In simple terms, there's those who want harsh penalties for any misjudgements and there's those who are more lenient, leading opposing views on some penalties. Both are valid positions.

name: Edd Straw
tweet: @E_R_Podcast @wearetherace @glennfreeman39 @SMitchellF1 I'm consistent in my position that the racing incident should be allowed to exist and that the rules can be problematic because they limit judgement to only a small number of parameters in a dynamic racing situation. That ties the hands of stewards.

name: Edd Straw
tweet: @E_R_Podcast @wearetherace @glennfreeman39 @SMitchellF1 Penalties should be used for irresponsible moves, extreme misjudgements. What's more, you are clearly suggesting British bias, so how does the fact I argued ideally Vettel shouldn't have been penalised in Canada last year square with that?

name: Edd Straw
tweet: @E_R_Podcast @wearetherace @glennfreeman39 @SMitchellF1 In my case, at no point have I suggested Monza '18 warranted a penalty. It was a similar thing - honest misjudgement from the driver on the inside. A racing incident doesn't mean it has to be exactly 50/50 and each must be judged on the exact situation.
